nodes.title: Implement HEEx in Temper
nodes.metadata_json:
{"branch":"main","confidence":80,"prompt":"I want to make a wild plan.

Using the Temper programming language (in the directory @docs/for-users/temper-docs/docs for finding the docs, @temper-regex-parser/ for example lib @prismora/ also for example to look at the language with reference)

we want to basically implement heex. Which is in @phoenix_live_view/ and @vscode-html-heex/ 

lets begin making a plan for this using temper's premise of literate programming

keep a document called INFO.md as a "cache" for as you go along"}

nodes.title: Completed research on Temper and HEEx architectures
Temper: literate programming via .temper.md, cross-compiles to Java/JS/Python/C#/Lua/Rust
Temper parser pattern: recursive descent with stateful Parser class, error collection via ListBuilder
HEEx architecture: 3-layer pipeline (tokenizer→parser→compiler), tokens include :tag/:close/:text/:body_expr/:eex
HEEx syntax: {expr} for interpolation, <.local> for local components, <Remote.Name> for remote, <:slot> for named slots
HEEx special attrs: :if for conditionals, :for for iteration, :key for list optimization, :let for slot bindings
Implementation approach: literate programming with 4 modules (ast/tokenizer/parser/renderer)
Research Temper documentation
Temper module structure: config.temper.md for metadata, ;;; separates preface/body/metadata, directory-based modules
Temper syntax: let for functions/vars, class with constructor params, interface with default impls, when for pattern matching
Research temper-regex-parser example
regex-parser: Parser class with chars/pos state, recursive descent (readOr→readSeq→readSingle), throws Bubble for errors
regex-parser exports: parse() returns AST, compile() returns Regex, slots for template composition
Research Phoenix LiveView HEEx implementation
HEEx tokenizer: stateful scanner producing :tag/:close/:text/:body_expr/:eex tokens with line/col tracking
HEEx parser: converts tokens to hierarchical AST with {:block, type, name, attrs, children, meta}
HEEx components: .name for local, Module.Name for remote, :name for slots, with :let for bindings
Research vscode-html-heex grammar
VSCode HEEx: dual-parsing approach, virtual document content for HTML/Elixir separation, bracket pairs for <% %>
Create heex/ project structure with literate programming files
Created literate programming project structure: config, ast, tokenizer, parser, renderer modules
Session paused: 4 main modules complete (ast, tokenizer, parser, renderer), exports and tests remaining

AST module: 337 lines defining 15+ types - Node interface, Location/Span for source tracking, Document/Text/Element/Component/Slot/Expression/EEx/EExBlock/Comment nodes, 4 Attribute types (Static/Dynamic/Spread/Special), ComponentType/EExType enums, void element detection

Tokenizer module: 720 lines - TokenType with 20+ variants (Text, TagOpen/Close/SelfClose/End, ComponentOpen/Close, SlotOpen/Close, AttrName/Equals/Value, ExprOpen/Close/Content, EExOpen/Output/Comment/Close/Content, CommentOpen/Close/Content, EOF)

Tokenizer: Stateful scanner class with pos/line/column tracking, error collection via ListBuilder, peek/advance/matches methods, character classification helpers (isWhitespace/isAlpha/isDigit/isNameChar)
Tokenizer scanning: tokenizeText (until < or {), tokenizeTag (handles closing/slot/component dispatch), tokenizeClosingTag, tokenizeSlotOpen, tokenizeComponentOpen with isLocal flag
Tokenizer attributes: tokenizeAttributes loop, tokenizeAttributeValue (dynamic {}/quoted/unquoted), tokenizeSpreadAttribute, tokenizeSpecialAttribute for :if/:for/:key
Tokenizer expressions: tokenizeExpression with brace depth tracking and string escape handling, tokenizeEEx for <%/%=/%# variants, tokenizeComment for <!-- -->
Parser module: 600 lines - Recursive descent parser with Parser class (tokens list, pos, errors ListBuilder), current/peek/peekNext/check/advance/expect methods
Parser entry: parse(input) -> tokenize -> parseTokens, parseChildren loop with closing tag detection for TagClose/ComponentClose/SlotClose
Parser dispatch: parseNode uses when/pattern-matching on token type to route to parseText/parseElement/parseComponent/parseSlot/parseExpression/parseEEx/parseComment
Parser elements: parseElement handles void elements (self-closing), recursive children parsing, closing tag validation with mismatch error reporting
Parser components: parseComponent distinguishes Local (.name) vs Remote (Module.Name) via ComponentType, parseComponentBody returns ComponentBodyResult with children and slots separated
Parser slots: parseSlot extracts :let binding from SpecialAttribute, handles self-closing slots, validates closing tag matches

Parser attributes: parseAttributes loop handles SpreadAttribute ({@expr}), SpecialAttribute (:if/:for/:key/:let), DynamicAttribute (name={expr}), StaticAttribute (name="val"), boolean attrs (no value)
Parser EEx blocks: isBlockStart detects if/case/cond/for/unless, parseEExBlock extracts blockType and expression, parseEExBlockBody recursively parses until isBlockClause (end/else/->)
Renderer module: 575 lines - Three output modes: renderHtml (HTML string), renderDebug (AST visualization), renderJson (tooling integration)
Renderer HTML: renderNode dispatches via when/pattern-match, renderElement handles void/self-closing, renderComponent renders children then named slots, renderSlot with <:name> syntax
Renderer attributes: renderAttributes handles all 4 types - StaticAttribute (name="val"), DynamicAttribute (name={expr}), SpreadAttribute ({expr}), SpecialAttribute (:kind={expr})
Renderer EEx: renderEEx formats output/comment/exec variants, renderEExBlock reconstructs block structure with do/else/end clauses
Renderer escaping: escapeHtml (& < >), escapeAttr (& " < >), jsonString (" \\ \n \r \t) - proper XSS prevention
Renderer debug: renderDebug produces indented tree view, renderDebugNode/renderDebugAttr show node types and content, newlines escaped as \\n
Renderer JSON: renderJson produces valid JSON, renderJsonNode handles all node types with type discriminators, renderJsonAttr for attribute types, jsonString for proper escaping
Config module: Package metadata (name, version, description, license, authors), backend-specific config (javaGroup, javaName, jsName, pyName, rustName), module imports graph
Design: Literate programming via .temper.md, three-stage pipeline (tokenize->parse->render), error-tolerant processing (collect errors vs fail fast), cross-platform AST output
Module dependencies: config imports ast/tokenizer/parser/renderer/exports/tests, ast standalone, tokenizer imports ast, parser imports ast+tokenizer, renderer imports ast
Missing: exports.temper.md - Public API surface re-exporting parse/tokenize/render functions
Missing: tests/tokenizer.temper.md - Unit tests for tokenizer: text, tags, components, slots, attributes, expressions, EEx, comments, error cases
Missing: tests/parser.temper.md - Unit tests for parser: elements, components, slots, nested structures, EEx blocks, error recovery
Missing: tests/integration.temper.md - End-to-end tests: parse then render roundtrip, complex templates, real Phoenix LiveView examples
Language choice: Temper vs native implementations
Option: Native Elixir implementation - Match Phoenix LiveView exactly but single-platform only
Option: TypeScript implementation - Good tooling ecosystem but JS-only
CHOSEN: Temper implementation - Write once, compile to Java/JS/Python/C#/Lua/Rust, fits httpeex cross-platform goal
Tokenizer architecture: Single-pass scanner vs multi-pass
Option: Multi-pass (Phoenix approach) - EEx.tokenize first, then HTML tokenize text segments. Requires EEx tokenizer dependency
CHOSEN: Single-pass scanner - Handle HTML, expressions {}, and EEx <%%> in unified pass. Self-contained, no external deps, simpler mental model
Option: Dual-parsing (VSCode approach) - Treat as HTML, extract Elixir regions to virtual documents. Good for IDE, not for AST building
Error handling strategy: Fail-fast vs error collection
Option: Fail-fast (throw on first error) - Simpler implementation but poor DX, user fixes one error at a time
CHOSEN: Error collection (ListBuilder<String>) - Collect all errors, throw Bubble at end. Better DX, matches temper-regex-parser pattern
Option: Result type (Ok/Err) - Functional approach, explicit error handling but verbose in Temper
Component identification: How to distinguish HTML tags from components
Option: tag_handler callback (Phoenix approach) - External classifier decides tag type at runtime. Flexible but requires dependency injection
CHOSEN: Syntax-based detection - .name=local component, Uppercase.Name=remote component, :name=slot. Self-contained, no callbacks needed
Option: Explicit markers (JSX approach) - All components uppercase only. Simpler but doesn't match HEEx conventions
AST node representation: Union type vs class hierarchy
Option: Tuple-based (Elixir approach) - {:block, type, name, attrs, children, meta}. Lightweight but no type safety
CHOSEN: Class hierarchy with Node interface - Element/Component/Slot/Expression/EEx classes. Type-safe, supports pattern matching via when
Option: Discriminated union - Single Node type with nodeType field. Simpler but less idiomatic Temper
Attribute type system: How to represent static vs dynamic vs special attributes
Option: Single attr type with variant field - {name, value, type: static|dynamic|spread|special}. Simpler but requires runtime checks
CHOSEN: Separate classes - StaticAttribute/DynamicAttribute/SpreadAttribute/SpecialAttribute. Type-safe dispatch in renderer via when
Option: Key-value pairs only - Lose type info, treat all as strings. Too lossy for proper rendering
EEx block handling: How to parse if/case/for control flow
Option: Flat tokens (keep start_expr/middle_expr/end_expr separate) - Parser builds tree later. Phoenix approach but complex state management
CHOSEN: Tokenize flat, parse into EExBlock with clauses - isBlockStart detects if/case/for, parseEExBlock builds clause list with children
Option: Pre-parse EEx separately - Two-pass: EEx structure first, then HTML. Clean separation but duplicate work
Renderer output modes: What formats to support
Option: HTML only - Simplest, but limits tooling use cases
CHOSEN: HTML + Debug + JSON - renderHtml for output, renderDebug for development, renderJson for tooling integration
Option: Visitor pattern - Abstract renderer, let consumers implement. More flexible but over-engineered for initial release
Module organization: How to structure the codebase
Option: Single file - All code in one module. Simple but unwieldy at 2000+ lines
CHOSEN: Pipeline modules - config/ast/tokenizer/parser/renderer/exports/tests. Each ~500 lines, clear dependencies, literate programming
Option: Feature-based modules - Group by feature (tags, components, expressions). Cross-cutting concerns but may fragment related code
Trade-off: Temper lacks dependent types, so void element detection uses runtime list check (voidElements.contains) rather than compile-time guarantees
Trade-off: ComponentType/EExType use enum-like classes with static fields rather than sealed classes - Temper doesn't have enum keyword yet
Trade-off: Expression nodes store raw code as String rather than parsing Elixir - out of scope for HEEx parser, would require separate Elixir parser
Insight from Phoenix: Their tokenizer uses continuation-passing ({:text, braces}, :script, :style, {:comment, line, col}) to handle special content modes
Insight from Phoenix: tag_handler.classify_type() and tag_handler.void?() callbacks allow runtime tag classification - we baked this into syntax instead
Insight from Phoenix: Parser uses stack-based tree building - push on tag open, pop on close, buffer accumulates children. Same pattern used here
Insight from temper-regex-parser: Parser class pattern with chars/pos/errors state, peek/advance/read methods - adopted directly
Insight from temper-regex-parser: throws Bubble for error propagation rather than Result type - matches Temper idioms
Insight from temper-regex-parser: Separate exports.temper file re-exports public API (parse, compile) - clean public surface
Insight from VSCode: isInsideElixirRegion scans for % delimited regions - good for tooling but loses structure
Insight from VSCode: getElixirVirtualContent replaces non-Elixir with spaces, preserves line/col for accurate diagnostics
Insight from VSCode: Language configuration defines bracket pairs <%/%>, <%=/%>, <%#/%> for auto-close - useful for future IDE integration
Temper feature used: class with constructor params (class Parser(tokens: List<Token>, var pos: Int)) - concise state encapsulation
Temper feature used: when pattern matching for node dispatch - when (node) { is Text -> ...; is Element -> ...; else -> ... }
Temper feature used: interface with default impls (interface Node { nodeType(): String; toString(): String; }) - polymorphic AST
Temper feature used: ListBuilder for mutable accumulation then .build()/.toList() for immutable result - efficient collection building
Temper feature used: StringBuilder for string concatenation - .append() then .build() - avoid O(n²) string concat
Chose Temper: Cross-platform compilation working, code compiles to all 6 backends, literate .temper.md format enables documentation-as-code
Chose single-pass scanner: Tokenizer is self-contained (~720 lines), handles HTML/expressions/EEx uniformly, no external dependencies
Chose error collection: Users see all parse errors at once, matches temper-regex-parser pattern, better DX than fix-one-at-a-time
Chose syntax-based detection: No runtime callbacks needed, tokenizer identifies .name/Uppercase.Name/:slot directly, cleaner architecture
Chose class hierarchy: Type-safe AST with Node interface, when pattern matching works cleanly, each node type has specific fields
Chose separate attribute classes: Renderer dispatches via when on StaticAttribute/DynamicAttribute/SpreadAttribute/SpecialAttribute, type-safe output
Chose EExBlock with clauses: Parser detects if/case/for via isBlockStart, builds structured EExBlock with EExClause list containing children
Chose HTML+Debug+JSON: Three render functions cover all use cases - renderHtml for production, renderDebug for development, renderJson for tooling
Chose pipeline modules: 5 focused modules (ast/tokenizer/parser/renderer + config), each ~500 lines, clear import dependencies, literate documentation
Create exports module and test files
Created exports module and 3 test files: exports.temper.md (public API), tests/tokenizer.temper.md (40+ tests), tests/parser.temper.md (50+ tests), tests/integration.temper.md (30+ roundtrip tests)
Exports module: Imports all types from ast (15 types), tokenizer (4 types), parser (3 functions), renderer (3 functions)

Exports API: renderToHtml/renderToDebug/renderToJson - renamed from renderHtml/renderDebug/renderJson for clearer public naming
Exports convenience: parseAndRender(String)->String for validation/normalization, parseAndValidate(String)->Boolean for quick checks
Exports re-exports: All AST node types (Document/Text/Element/Component/Slot/Expression/EEx/Comment), attribute types, supporting types, Token/TokenType for advanced use
Exports metadata: VERSION='0.1.0', NAME='heex' constants for runtime version checking
Tokenizer tests setup: assertTokenTypes helper compares token type list, assertTokenValues helper compares token value list - both throw Bubble on mismatch

Integration tests setup: roundtrip(input) helper parses then renders to HTML, assertRoundtrip(input) re-parses output to verify validity
Integration tests - basic roundtrip: plain text, simple element, self-closing, element with content, nested elements - 5 tests verifying parse->render preserves structure

Integration tests - real Phoenix components: modal with :title/:footer slots, JS.hide callback in attribute, phx-click handlers - 1 test

Test strategy: How to organize and structure tests
Option: Single test file - All tests in one module. Simpler but harder to navigate
CHOSEN: Three-layer tests - tokenizer.temper.md (unit), parser.temper.md (unit), integration.temper.md (e2e). Matches pipeline architecture
Option: Feature-based tests - Organize by feature (components, slots, EEx). Good for coverage but crosses module boundaries
Chose three-layer tests: tokenizer (27 tests), parser (36 tests), integration (30 tests) - clear separation, each layer tests its module in isolation then integration verifies pipeline
Exports API design: How to expose public interface
Option: Direct re-export - Just re-export internal functions unchanged. Simpler but exposes internal naming
CHOSEN: Thin wrapper functions - parseTemplate/tokenizeTemplate/renderToHtml with clearer names, plus convenience functions parseAndRender/parseAndValidate
Option: Full facade - Wrap everything with validation, options objects, builder pattern. Over-engineered for initial release
Chose thin wrappers: 5 main functions (parseTemplate/tokenizeTemplate/renderToHtml/renderToDebug/renderToJson), 2 convenience (parseAndRender/parseAndValidate), all types re-exported for advanced use
HEEx implementation complete: 9 modules totaling 3868 lines - ast (336), tokenizer (719), parser (598), renderer (574), config (78), exports (155), plus 3 test files (1408 lines)

nodes.metadata_json:
{"branch":"main","confidence":90,"prompt":"okay, so now lets get to github... we want to start in the following way:
1. we have a 'main' repo with the temper code here
2. we have 6 repos that are created for ts, lua, java, python, c#, and rust
3. the gh actions builds for the main repo when merging to main end up building each of the supported languages package
4. that package generation then pushes over to the 6 sub-repos
5. those sub-repos tag a release and take the build code and patch it all in
6. EVERY one of these repos has proper CI/CD
7. We still have CI/CD on the main temper repo as the releasable source of truth
8. We begin writing docs per-language, making a github pages site for each that will publish them from markdown and really show how this can integrate into any of the other languages with example code in-repo in an examples/ dir

User clarified: this is a PERSONAL project published under notactuallytreyanastasio, NOT official Temper code. Package publishing is deferred - focus on build → distribute → tag pipeline first."}
